# Stock: malformed and hostile HTTP/1.1 request framing.
#
# Module-agnostic by construction -- every `expect status=` here is a
# PARSER-LEVEL verdict. nginx and angie validate the request line and headers
# before any module handler runs, so a 400 below comes from the core,
# identically, no matter what is configured on the location. That is what makes
# these safe to hoist as stock.
#
# Hoisted from nginx-http-shield-module's t/prober/rules/03-malformed.rule.
# Two of that file's ten cases were dropped rather than hoisted: the
# absolute-form request target and the duplicate-Content-Type payload case both
# assert shield's own WAF verdict (403), which is a module opinion rather than a
# parser fact. See rules/stock/README.md.
#
# Target is /__probe throughout: it is the one location EVERY harness consumer
# has, so no case here needs a passthrough location or a per-consumer status
# knob. GET-only, which matters below.
#
# Every status in this file was MEASURED against nginx 1.31.3, not assumed. Two
# results contradict the intuitive guess and are called out where they occur.

name    request with no Host header is rejected (HTTP/1.1 requires Host)
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Connection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

name    NUL byte inside the query string is rejected by the URI parser
send    GET /__probe?x=1\x00234 HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

name    NUL byte inside the URI path is rejected by the URI parser
send    GET /__prob\x00e HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# A raw NUL is rejected wherever it sits in the request target. Both positions
# are asserted because a parser that TRUNCATED at the NUL rather than rejecting
# it would still fail the path case (the URI becomes /__prob, a 404) while
# serving the query case perfectly -- so one case alone cannot tell the two
# behaviours apart.

# %00 is where path and query genuinely DIVERGE, and it is the case most likely
# to be written wrong from memory. Only the PATH is percent-decoded during URI
# normalization, so a decoded NUL is caught there and 400s. The query string is
# not decoded by the core parser at all, so %00 arrives as three ordinary ASCII
# bytes and the request is ACCEPTED (200 from /__probe).
name    percent-encoded NUL in the URI path is rejected
send    GET /__probe%00x HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

name    percent-encoded NUL in the query string is accepted, not rejected
send    GET /__probe?x=%00y HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# Bare LF instead of CRLF is ACCEPTED -- measured, not assumed. nginx takes a
# bare LF as a line terminator throughout the request, so this is well-formed as
# far as core is concerned and reaches the handler. Asserting 400 here (the
# intuitive guess, and what a strict reading of RFC 9112 2.2 would suggest) would
# have failed against a correct server.
name    bare LF line endings instead of CRLF are still accepted
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\n
send    Host: prober\nConnection: close\n\n
expect  status=200
probe   zone.present == true
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# Request smuggling primitives. Both are rejected by the parser before the
# handler runs, which is why they can assert a status here while the chunked
# cases in malformed-body.rule cannot.
name    duplicate Content-Length headers are rejected
send    POST /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\n
send    Content-Length: 5\r\n
send    Content-Length: 6\r\n
send    Connection: close\r\n\r\n
send    hello
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

name    Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding together are rejected
send    POST /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\n
send    Content-Length: 5\r\n
send    Transfer-Encoding: chunked\r\n
send    Connection: close\r\n\r\n
send    5\r\nhello\r\n0\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# Note both cases above are POSTs to a GET-only location, yet assert 400 rather
# than the 405 that location answers a well-formed POST with. That IS the point:
# the header conflict is caught in ngx_http_process_request_headers, before
# method dispatch, so the 400 proves the parser rejected the framing rather than
# the handler rejecting the method. If either case ever reports 405, the
# smuggling check silently stopped running.

# The header-size pair. The first is the CONTROL: 2560 bytes of value sits well
# under the default large_client_header_buffers (4 8k), so it must parse
# normally and reach the handler. Without it the oversized case below could pass
# because the server rejects ANY request carrying an X-Filler header -- a
# different bug that would look identical from the oversized case alone.
name    large but legal header value is parsed normally
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\n
send    X-Filler:
repeat  40 AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
send    \r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
probe   zone.present == true
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# 128 * 64 = 8192 bytes of value alone, which is the whole default buffer before
# the request line and the other headers are even counted, so both servers
# reject at the parser with 400.
name    oversized header value is rejected by the parser
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\n
send    X-Filler:
repeat  128 AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
send    \r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0

# 1600 * 64 = 102400 bytes in one header line: an order of magnitude past the
# buffer rather than just over it, to drive the reject path with a length that
# would wrap a 16-bit size or a signed short in a module's own header handling.
# Same 400 -- the case is about the SIZE reaching that code, not about the
# status differing from the case above.
name    a ~100KB header line is rejected without disturbing the worker
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\n
send    X-Filler:
repeat  1600 AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
send    \r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=400
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
delta   pool.cycle_large == 0

# The worker must still be alive and the zone still coherent after all of the
# above. If any earlier case killed it, this one fails on connect -- one closer
# at file end, the same idiom as shield's 03-malformed.rule, because a crash on
# case N surfaces as a connection error on case N+1 rather than as a wrong
# status on case N itself.
#
# No explicit pid assertion: the harness snapshots the probe before and after
# EVERY case and fails the case outright when the worker pid moved
# (eval_pid_stable, prober/assert.c), so a `probe pid ==` line here would only
# restate a check that already ran unconditionally on all of them.
name    worker survives the malformed batch and the zone is still coherent
send    GET /__probe HTTP/1.1\r\n
send    Host: prober\r\nConnection: close\r\n\r\n
expect  status=200
probe   zone.present == true
probe   flavor ~ ngi
delta   fds == 0
delta   pool.cycle_used == 0
